text: Good afternoon, everyone.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: My paper is Incidence and Prediction of Contrast-Induced Nephropathy.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The use of contrast media is required in many applications of modern diagnostic imaging.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: However, their use is known to have complications, one of which is the deterioration of renal function.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Contrast induced nephropathy is defined as the impairment of renal function and is measured either as a 25% increase in serum creatinine from baseline or a 0.5 mg per deciliter increase in absolute value within two to three days of IV contrast administration.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Contrast induced nephropathy is the third leading cause of hospital acquired acute renal failure.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: It has been associated with increased morbidity, extended length of hospital stay, and increased costs.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The impairment of renal function is permanent in some cases with the risk of progression towards chronic renal failure.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: CIN by itself may even be an independent mortality risk factor.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The reported incidence of CIN might be an underestimation since most patients do not remain hospitalized for long enough.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: CIN suffers from a lack of consensus, making it difficult to compare studies, especially in terms of the efficacy of various treatment modalities.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The objective of the study was to know the incidence of CIN, to find the risk factors for the development of CIN, and to develop a simple risk score for prediction of CIN in patients undergoing diagnostic cardiac catheterization and PCIN.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Materials and methods.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Study design, prospective, non-interventional.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Type of study, observational, open cohort.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Setting, Department of Cardiology, Krishna Institute of Medical Sciences.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Sample size, 304 patients.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Inclusion criteria, all consecutive patients undergoing diagnostic cardiac catheterization and or PCI staying in the hospital for at least two days or willing to revisit the hospital on the third day were included in the study.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Exclusion criteria,
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Patients with pre-existing end-stage renal disease requiring dialysis, patients with history of exposure to contrast media within one week of index procedure, and patients in shock.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Materials, patient information form in English, Hindi, Telugu, and Urdu languages, informed consent form in the same languages, pro forma for data collection, lab materials for sample collection, and SPSS version 17.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Approval was obtained from the institute's scientific and ethics committees before starting the project.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Each patient was provided a patient information form in their language of choice and asked to sign on a consent form after satisfactory explanation.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Blood and urine samples were collected from all the patients before the index procedure.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Another blood sample was taken two days after the procedure, either on inpatient or outpatient basis.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The remaining investigations were done as a routine by the hospital, and the reports were obtained from the hospital records.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: All the patients underwent thorough history taking and clinical examination.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The samples were analyzed in the laboratories of Kim's Hospital.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: BMI, creatinine clearance, and EGFR were calculated using the respective formulae.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Prior to the index procedure, the hydration and amount of hydration given to the patient was at the discretion of the cardiologist.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: One of the following contrast media was used for the procedure at the discretion of the cardiologist, ionic, non-ionic, or isoosmolar.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: All the data and the investigations were tabulated in Microsoft Excel.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: SPSS version 17 was used to analyze the data.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The patients were divided into two groups, patients who got CIN and patients who did not get CIN.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: And 51 factors were compared for the correlation for development of CIN.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Initially, chi-square test and student T-test were done.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Then variables with p values less than 0.05 were analyzed for their correlation with CIN using Pearson's and Spearman correlations.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Observations and results.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Out of the 304 patients, 80 subjects developed CIN, which was an incidence of 26.31%.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The patients were divided into two groups, CIN and non-CIN groups.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: These are the student t-test results.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Diastolic BP, CRP, HDL, VLDL, triglycerides, fasting blood sugar, creatinine, EGFR, and creatinine clearance had p-values of less than 0.05.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: These are the chi-square test results.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Gender, ECG, hypertrophy, and arrhythmia, eco-valve abnormality, and pulmonary hypertension had p-values of less than 0.05.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: This shows the comparison of diastolic blood pressure, which was significantly lower in CIN patients.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The CRP was significantly higher in CIN patients.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Surprisingly, the average lipid levels were lower in CIN patients than in non-CIN patients.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Fasting blood sugar was significantly higher in patients with CIN.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Again, surprisingly, the baseline serum creatinine, the average EGFR and average creatinine clearance were better in CIN patients.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: More number of females, a bigger percentage of females developed CIN compared to males.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Hypertrophin arrhythmias were also significantly associated with CIN.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: valve abnormalities and pulmonary hypertension also were associated.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: However, none of the variables in the model showed strong or significant correlation with CIN.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Failure of variables to show significance might have been due to the small sample size discussion.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The incidence of CIN was compared in diagnostic and interventional catheterization.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Incidence was found to be more in people undergoing coronary interventions compared to diagnostic catheterization.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Pre-existing renal dysfunction is thought to be a risk factor for CIN, but there was a high incidence of CIN in the study even in patients with normal renal function.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: This might have an important practical implication in the prevention of CIN.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The incidence of CIN was compared in patients receiving different types of contrast media.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The number of patients in whom isosmolar contrast was used was very small to come to a definite conclusion, but there seemed to be decreased incidence in people given isosmolar contrast.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: In this study, there was found to be a trend towards increase in incidence of CIN with an increase in volume of contrast used.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Suggestions, minimizing the amount of contrast used in each patient, aggressive hydration therapy in all patients including those with normal baseline renal function, avoiding repeat procedures at short intervals as far as possible.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Limitations of the study, it had a small sample size with all the patients admitted to a single center.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Serum creatinine as a marker of renal function has its limitations.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The pre-procedure measures to prevent CIN were not uniform in all the patients.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: Different types of contrast media used in different patients might have affected the results of the study.
speaker: SPEAKER_02

text: The post-procedure serum creatinine was measured on the third day, so patients who might have developed CIN after this period would have been missed, leading to underestimation of the incidence of CIN.
speaker: SPEAKER_02
